  "footnotes": [
    "Tocharians: a mysterious ancient Indo-European people who inhabited the Tarim Basin for millennia; their language (Tocharian A / B) was discovered in manuscripts from Dunhuang and Turfan in the early 20th century; genetically linked to the Yamnaya steppe peoples, they were already settled in the Tarim Basin by c.2000 BCE, making them among the earliest Indo-European migrants into East Asia",
    "Kara-Khanid Khanate (c.940–1212): the first Turkic Islamic state, founded when the ruler Satuq Bughra Khan converted to Islam c.934; Kashgar was one of their capitals; their conversion spread Islam eastward into the Tarim and ended Buddhism in western Xinjiang; the Kara-Khanids conquered Buddhist Khotan in 1006",
    "Gaochang Uyghurs / Turfan Uyghurs (高昌回鶻, 866–1209): after the Uyghur Khaganate collapsed under a Kyrgyz invasion in 840, a branch of Uyghurs fled to the Turfan oasis and founded a Buddhist kingdom that became a major center of Silk Road culture; they preserved Manichaean, Buddhist, and Nestorian texts; they voluntarily submitted to Genghis Khan in 1209",
    "Ya'qub Beg / Yettishar (1865–1877): a military commander from Kokand who exploited the Dungan Rebellion to carve out a short-lived state (Yettishar means 'Seven Cities'); recognized by the Ottoman Empire and the United Kingdom; destroyed by a Qing reconquest under General Zuo Zongtang",
    "First East Turkestan Republic (1933–1934): a short-lived Islamic republic in Kashgar, founded during a Uyghur and Kirghiz uprising; quickly suppressed by Sheng Shicai with Soviet assistance; represents the first use of the name 'East Turkestan' as a political entity",
    "Second East Turkestan Republic (ETR2, 1944–1949): a Soviet-backed leftist republic in the Ili/Kuldzha region; controlled roughly three prefectures; its military was incorporated into the People's Liberation Army after the PRC's founding; key ETR2 leaders died in a suspicious plane crash en route to Beijing in 1949"
  ]
